To extract an integer value from a double variable in Delphi, you can use the trunc function. The trunc function truncates a real number to an integer value without rounding.

For example:

```
var
  myDouble: Double;
  myInt: Integer;

myDouble := 10.99;
myInt := trunc(myDouble);

// myInt will now hold the value 10
```

In this example, the trunc function is used to extract the integer value from the myDouble variable and store it in the myInt variable. The resulting value is 10, which is the integer value of the myDouble variable after truncating it.

To round down to the nearest integer in Delphi, you can use the Floor function. The Floor function returns the largest integer value that is less than or equal to the input value. Here is an example:

```
var
  myDouble: Double;
  myInt: Integer;

myDouble := 5.8;
myInt := Floor(myDouble);

// myInt will now hold the value 5
```

In this example, the Floor function is used to round down the value of the myDouble variable to the nearest integer and store it in the myInt variable. The resulting value is 5 because it is the largest integer value that is less than or equal to the myDouble value of 5.8.
